[Event "French Defense: Key Variations"]
[Result "*"]

{The French Defense is a solid counter-attacking system. Black accepts a space disadvantage but gets a strong pawn structure and clear plans.} 1. e4 e6 {The French Defense. Black prepares ...d5 to challenge the center immediately.} 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {The Advance Variation — White grabs space but must defend the pawn chain.} (3. Nc3 {The main line. White defends e4.} Bb4 {The Winawer Variation — the sharpest French.} (3... Nf6 {The Classical French.} 4. Bg5 Be7 (4... dxe4 {The Burn Variation.} 5. Nxe4 Be7 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 {Solid for Black.}) 5. e5 Nfd7 6. Bxe7 Qxe7 7. f4 {White has a strong pawn center but Black will attack it with ...c5, ...f6.}) (3... dxe4 {The Rubinstein Variation — solid and simple.} 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 {An equal, quiet position.}) 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 {The main line Winawer. White has the bishop pair and a strong center; Black will attack c3 and d4.} 7. Qg4 {Attacking g7 immediately.} Qc7 (7... O-O 8. Bd3 Nbc6 {Black is solid but must be careful about the kingside.})) (3. exd5 {The Exchange Variation — drawish but not toothless.} exd5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bd3 Bd6 6. O-O O-O 7. Bg5 {Symmetrical pawn structure. White has a tiny initiative.}) c5 {The key break against the Advance. Black attacks the pawn chain at its base.} 4. c3 {Supporting d4.} Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 {Pressuring b2 and d4.} (5... Bd7 {A flexible developing move.} 6. Be2 Nge7 7. Na3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Nf5 {Black targets d4.}) 6. a3 {Preparing b4 and preventing ...Bb4.} c4 {Fixing the pawn structure. Black will play on the queenside, White on the kingside.} (6... Nh6 {Heading for f5 to pressure d4.} 7. b4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Nf5 {Both sides have clear plans.}) 7. Nbd2 Na5 8. Be2 Bd7 9. O-O Ne7 {A typical Advance French structure. Black will play ...Nf5, ...Be7, ...O-O with pressure on d4.} *
